      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"1-hydroxypropan-2-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydroxyacetone\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h4H,2H2,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H6O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"propan-2-one\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetone\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Acetone cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO/c1-4(2,6)3-5/h6H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H9NOS\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H9NOS/c1-4(2,6)3(5)7/h6H,1-2H3,(H2,5,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-4(2)5(7)3-6/h4-5,7H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(7)3-6/h4-5H,7H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H12N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"2-Amino-4-methylpentanenitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H12N2/c1-5(2)3-6(8)4-7/h5-6H,3,8H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"disulfane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Disulfane\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-Ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"L-Valine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>50 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 is adsorbed onto the Fe3S4 greigite surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe4S4] clusters. Molecular hydrogen dissociatively adsorbs on the mineral surface, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 via a two-electron transfer to formate (HCOO-). The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the highly reducing, alkaline vent conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is a well-established hydrothermal reaction analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway. Demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) and Herschy et al. (2014), showing that native iron-sulfur minerals catalyze CO2 fixation under simulated alkaline vent conditions. This provides the C1 feedstock for downstream formaldehyde production.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"370-470K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Subseafloor hydrothermal conditions, Fe0 as strong reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Formate is further reduced on Fe3O4/Fe0 surfaces through a two-electron reduction that removes one oxygen, yielding formaldehyde (H2CO). Elemental iron provides the driving force for reduction, being oxidized to Fe2+ in the process. Magnetite serves as the catalytic surface facilitating hydrogen transfer.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reduction of formate to formaldehyde under hydrothermal conditions is supported by work on serpentinization-driven organic synthesis (McCollom & Seewald, 2007, EPSL; Seewald et al., 2006). Formaldehyde is a critical C1 building block for the formose reaction that produces the C3 sugar precursors needed for the downstream cyanosulfidic valine pathway. This step connects hydrothermal CO2 fixation to surface sugar chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde (formose initiation)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline conditions (pH 10-11), Ca(OH)2 present, evaporitic pool setting\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo an aldol-type condensation catalyzed by Ca(OH)2 and clay mineral surfaces. The Cannizzaro reaction provides initial glycolaldehyde through disproportionation, and subsequent aldol addition of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde creates C3 sugars. Borate minerals stabilize the sugar products against degradation by forming borate esters.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The formose reaction (Butlerow, 1861) is the classical prebiotic route to sugars from formaldehyde. Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) demonstrated that borate minerals stabilize sugars (especially ribose) against degradation, enabling productive formose chemistry. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes the condensation and concentrates reactants. This produces the glycolaldehyde intermediate needed for C3 sugar synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to dihydroxyacetone (formose chain extension)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"borate minerals, Ca(OH)2\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline formose conditions, borate stabilization, wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glycolaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to form glyceraldehyde (C3 aldose), which then isomerizes via a 1,2-hydride shift (Lobry de Bruyn-van Ekenstein rearrangement) to dihydroxyacetone (C3 ketose). Borate complexation stabilizes the triose products and shifts the equilibrium toward the ketose form.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formose-type aldol chain extension from glycolaldehyde to C3 sugars is well documented (Breslow, 1959; Orgel, 2000). Borate stabilization of the triose is demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004, Science). Dihydroxyacetone is the specific C3 sugar feedstock required for the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic valine pathway.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Glycolaldehyde to hydroxyacetone via formose methylation\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite, borate minerals\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Formose reaction conditions, alternative branching pathway under slightly different pH/concentration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Under formose conditions, glycolaldehyde undergoes retro-aldol/aldol rearrangement with formaldehyde, producing hydroxyacetone (acetol, CH3COCH2OH) as an alternative C3 product alongside dihydroxyacetone. The methyl group of hydroxyacetone arises from dehydration-rearrangement of an intermediate aldol adduct.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydroxyacetone is a known product of the formose reaction alongside dihydroxyacetone and glyceraldehyde (Mizuno & Weiss, 1974). Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) explicitly use hydroxyacetone as an alternative starting sugar for the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. This provides a second upstream entry point to the acetone hub.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Dihydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu0)\", \"hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions: Cu0 as single-electron reductant, H2S as co-reductant, surface evaporitic pool\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper acts as a single-electron reductant in concert with hydrogen sulfide, stripping both hydroxymethyl groups from dihydroxyacetone and reducing the C3 backbone to acetone. Cu0 is oxidized to Cu+ or Cu2+ during the transformation, while H2S is oxidized to disulfane (H2S2).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this reductive deoxygenation as Step 1 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. Copper and H2S are essential reagents in their unified cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework that converts sugar feedstocks into ketone intermediates suitable for downstream nitrile chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu0)\", \"hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions: Cu0 as single-electron reductant, H2S as co-reductant\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Copper/H2S-mediated reductive removal of the hydroxyl group from hydroxyacetone (acetol), yielding acetone. The mechanism is analogous to rxn_006 but requires removal of only one hydroxymethyl group.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as an alternative upstream entry to the acetone hub from a different sugar derivative. This provides pathway redundancy: both DHA and hydroxyacetone converge on the same acetone intermediate under identical cyanosulfidic conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin formation: acetone + HCN\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu0)\", \"hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic pool conditions, mildly basic pH favoring CN- nucleophile\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide ion (CN-) to the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetone. The cyanide attacks the sp2 carbon, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the tertiary cyanohydrin (acetone cyanohydrin). The symmetrical dimethyl substitution of acetone produces a single cyanohydrin product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this cyanohydrin formation as Step 2 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. This is a classic Kiliani-type reaction (ketone variant) that introduces the C-CN bond that will ultimately become the carboxylic acid group of valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Thioamide formation: cyanohydrin + H2S\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu0)\", \"hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions, H2S acts as both reagent and part of the redox environment\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"H2S adds across the nitrile (C\u2261N) triple bond of the cyanohydrin. The sulfur nucleophile attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, and proton transfer completes the conversion to a thioamide (C(=S)NH2). This activates the nitrile for subsequent reductive chemistry by replacing the strong C\u2261N triple bond with a more reactive thioamide functionality.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 3 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. Thioamide formation is a key step in the cyanosulfidic framework: conversion of nitriles to thioamides via H2S activates the molecule for the critical Cu-mediated reductive rearrangement that builds the branched valine carbon skeleton.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive rearrangement with chain extension (Cu/H2S-mediated)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu0)\", \"hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"elemental copper (Cu0)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic conditions, Cu0 as single-electron reductant, H2S as co-reductant and sulfur source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"This is a complex, multi-step cyanosulfidic transformation. The thioamide undergoes reductive rearrangement mediated by copper and hydrogen sulfide. The thioamide nitrogen is lost, and a new C\u2013C bond is formed by incorporation of a second equivalent of HCN. Elemental copper acts as a single-electron reductant, while H2S provides reducing equivalents and sulfur acts as a leaving group (forming disulfane, H2S2). The net result is chain extension: the C4 thioamide is converted to a C5 alpha-hydroxynitrile with an isopropyl branch, establishing the valine carbon skeleton.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 4 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway \u2014 the critical C\u2013C bond-forming step that builds the branched-chain architecture unique to valine. This is the most mechanistically complex step in the network and represents the key innovation of the cyanosulfidic approach: using Cu/H2S redox chemistry to achieve C-C bond formation through thioamide intermediates.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker-type amination of alpha-hydroxynitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental copper (Cu0)\", \"hydrogen sulfide (H2S)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Cyanosulfidic pool, NH3 available from volcanic outgassing or HCN hydrolysis\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic substitution of the alpha-hydroxyl group by ammonia. The OH is displaced by NH3, converting the hydroxynitrile to an aminonitrile. This is a Strecker-type amination step \u2014 the replacement of OH by NH2 at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile \u2014 producing the direct aminonitrile precursor of valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 5 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. The Strecker-type amination converts the alpha-hydroxynitrile to the aminonitrile, setting up the final hydrolysis to the amino acid. This reaction is well-precedented in prebiotic chemistry (Strecker, 1854; Miller, 1957).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile to L-valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface catalysis)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Hydrolysis in aqueous pool, possibly aided by wet-dry cycling and mild heating\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the nitrile group of the aminonitrile to the carboxylic acid. Water attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-methylbutanamide), which further hydrolyzes to the free carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. This is the final Strecker-type hydrolysis step that converts the aminonitrile to L-valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as the final step (Step 6) of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is thermodynamically favorable and kinetically accessible under mild aqueous conditions, especially with clay mineral catalysis (Ferris et al., 1996).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile to L-valine (Pathway 2)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay surface catalysis)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Hydrolysis with concomitant chain shortening, aqueous pool conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolysis of the nitrile group of the C6 aminonitrile with concomitant loss of one carbon (chain shortening), converting the C6 aminonitrile to the C5 amino acid valine. The chain shortening may occur through a retro-aldol or decarboxylative mechanism under the cyanosulfidic conditions, releasing one CH2 unit as formaldehyde or CO2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) described this as an alternative route to valine from the C6 aminonitrile produced through the hydroxyacetone branch of the cyanosulfidic network. The chain-shortening mechanism remains an open question in the literature.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_021\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (>100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis at black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbon monoxide and hydrogen gas undergo Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces, producing a mixture of hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes. Isobutyraldehyde (2-methylpropanal) is a branched C4 aldehyde product formed through chain growth and branching on the mineral surface. CO adsorbs dissociatively, and sequential hydrogenation/chain growth steps build the branched carbon skeleton.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of aldehydes and hydrocarbons on magnetite under hydrothermal conditions was demonstrated by McCollom et al. (1999, EPSL) and Rushdi & Simoneit (2001). Branched aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde are plausible products of FTT synthesis, providing a hydrothermal route to the Strecker aldehyde precursor of valine.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (clay)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Strecker conditions: aldehyde + NH3 + HCN in aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Classical Strecker synthesis: (1) Ammonia attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde to form a hemiaminal, which dehydrates to an imine (Schiff base). (2) Cyanide ion (CN-) then adds to the electrophilic imine carbon in a nucleophilic addition, yielding 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile \u2014 the same aminonitrile produced by the cyanosulfidic pathway. This provides a direct, well-characterized route from a branched aldehyde to the valine aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is one of the oldest and most established prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Strecker, 1854; Miller, 1953). Miller's spark discharge experiments demonstrated that branched-chain amino acids including valine are produced via Strecker chemistry from aldehydes generated in the reducing atmosphere. The use of isobutyraldehyde as the specific aldehyde precursor for valine Strecker synthesis is described in standard prebiotic chemistry references (Miller & Orgel, 1974).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_020\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_022\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite (FeS2), mackinawite (FeS)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, FeS/FeS2 surface catalysis, NH3 from vent fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reductive amination of the alpha-keto acid on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. The carbonyl oxygen of alpha-ketoisovalerate is attacked by ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base), which is then reduced by H2 or FeS-derived electrons to yield L-valine. The iron-sulfur mineral surface provides both the catalytic site and the reducing equivalents for imine reduction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces is supported by the work of Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Letters) and Barge et al. (2019, PNAS), who demonstrated amino acid synthesis from keto acids and ammonia under hydrothermal conditions. This provides a direct hydrothermal route to valine that bypasses the surface cyanosulfidic pathway entirely, representing an alternative environmental context for valine formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal synthesis of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and formaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_020\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4), magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Multi-step process: CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite, then aldol with formaldehyde and reduction/dehydration\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-ketoisovalerate is synthesized through a multi-step process on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces: (1) CO2 is reduced to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite surfaces (analogous to reductive TCA cycle intermediates). (2) Pyruvate undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde and a second carbon unit, followed by reduction and dehydration/rearrangement to yield the branched C5 alpha-keto acid. The mineral surfaces template the carbon-carbon bond-forming steps.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction is partially speculative but grounded in demonstrated hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate (Cody et al., 2000, Science; Varma et al., 2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) and the general principle that alpha-keto acids are central hubs of prebiotic metabolism. The specific construction of the branched C5 skeleton from C1/C3 units on mineral surfaces extends the demonstrated chemistry of CO2 fixation on iron-sulfur minerals. This step is necessary to connect the hydrothermal reductive amination route (rxn_016) to the upstream feedstock network.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Full Hydrothermal-to-Surface Cyanosulfidic Route via DHA\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete pathway from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through formose sugar synthesis to cyanosulfidic valine production via dihydroxyacetone. Represents the most complete environmental interconnection from deep-sea vent CO2 to surface amino acid.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Full Hydrothermal-to-Surface Cyanosulfidic Route via Hydroxyacetone\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete pathway from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through formose chemistry to cyanosulfidic valine production via hydroxyacetone. Parallels P1 but uses the alternative C3 sugar feedstock.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-only Cyanosulfidic Route from Dihydroxyacetone\",\n      \"description\": \"The primary Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway starting from dihydroxyacetone assumed available in surface pools. Six-step sequence: reductive deoxygenation, cyanohydrin formation, thioamide formation, reductive rearrangement, amination, hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface-only Cyanosulfidic Route from Hydroxyacetone\",\n      \"description\": \"The parallel Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway starting from hydroxyacetone. Converges with P3 at the acetone hub.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic Pathway 2 via C6 Aminonitrile (from DHA)\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative cyanosulfidic route that produces valine from the C6 aminonitrile (2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile) through hydrolysis with chain shortening. Upstream uses DHA route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanosulfidic Pathway 2 via C6 Aminonitrile (from Hydroxyacetone)\",\n      \"description\": \"Alternative cyanosulfidic route via C6 aminonitrile using hydroxyacetone as the upstream sugar feedstock.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch to Surface Strecker Route\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde produced by hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite undergoes classical Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3 in surface pools, converging at the aminonitrile hub before hydrolysis to valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_019\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Reductive Amination Route\",\n      \"description\": \"Direct hydrothermal route: alpha-ketoisovalerate synthesized on iron-sulfur minerals undergoes reductive amination with ammonia on pyrite/mackinawite surfaces to yield valine. Entirely hydrothermal, bypassing surface chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Full CO2-to-Valine Hydrothermal Reductive Amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Complete hydrothermal pathway from CO2 through formate, formaldehyde, and alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine via reductive amination. Represents the deepest hydrothermal route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_017\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_020\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Hybrid Hydrothermal-Surface Route: Formaldehyde to Strecker via Formose\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal formaldehyde feeds formose chemistry producing glycolaldehyde and DHA in surface pools, with DHA entering the cyanosulfidic pathway. This traces the longest environmental interconnection chain.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_016\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"description\": \"Formaldehyde \u2014 Central C1 hub connecting hydrothermal CO2 fixation to surface formose chemistry\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetone \u2014 Key convergence point where two sugar feedstocks (DHA and hydroxyacetone) merge before entering the nitrile-based skeleton assembly\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrogen cyanide \u2014 Essential C1 nitrogen source used in cyanohydrin formation, reductive chain extension, and Strecker synthesis\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"description\": \"2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile \u2014 Convergence point containing the complete C5 branched valine skeleton, feeding into both C5 aminonitrile (amination) and C6 aminonitrile routes\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"description\": \"2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile \u2014 Final aminonitrile convergence point reached by both the cyanosulfidic pathway (via amination) and the Strecker route (from isobutyraldehyde)\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "L-Valine", "overall_strategy": "The network constructs L-valine through multiple convergent prebiotic routes anchored in the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework. The primary pathway proceeds from C3 sugar derivatives (dihydroxyacetone, hydroxyacetone) through reductive deoxygenation to acetone (a central hub), followed by cyanohydrin formation, thioamide conversion, Cu/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement with chain extension, Strecker-type amination, and nitrile hydrolysis. Upstream hydrothermal chemistry provides C1 feedstocks (formate, formaldehyde) via CO2 reduction on iron-sulfur minerals, which feed into surface formose chemistry to generate the C3 sugar precursors. A parallel Strecker route via isobutyraldehyde (from Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis) and a hydrothermal reductive amination route via alpha-ketoisovalerate provide alternative environmental pathways to valine. The network features five hub molecules (formaldehyde, acetone, HCN, 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile, and 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile) creating dense interconnection and redundancy across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "Carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "Hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "oxidane", "common_name": "Water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "formonitrile", "common_name": "Hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "Hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "H3N", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "Ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "CHO", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "Formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "Formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyacetaldehyde", "common_name": "Glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,4H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C3H6O3", "iupac_name": "1,3-dihydroxypropan-2-one", "common_name": "Dihydroxyacetone", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H6O2", "iupac_name": "1-hydroxypropan-2-one", "common_name": "Hydroxyacetone", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h4H,2H2,1H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C3H6O", "iupac_name": "propan-2-one", "common_name": "Acetone", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H7NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanenitrile", "common_name": "Acetone cyanohydrin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO/c1-4(2,6)3-5/h6H,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H9NOS", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide", "common_name": "2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H9NOS/c1-4(2,6)3(5)7/h6H,1-2H3,(H2,5,7)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H9NO", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-4(2)5(7)3-6/h4-5,7H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(7)3-6/h4-5H,7H2,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C6H12N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile", "common_name": "2-Amino-4-methylpentanenitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H12N2/c1-5(2)3-6(8)4-7/h5-6H,3,8H2,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "H2S2", "iupac_name": "disulfane", "common_name": "Disulfane", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "Isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-Ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "Carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "L-Valine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 reduction to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (>50 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, pH 9-11, H2-rich fluids from serpentinization"}, "mechanism": "CO2 is adsorbed onto the Fe3S4 greigite surface, which is structurally analogous to biological [Fe4S4] clusters. Molecular hydrogen dissociatively adsorbs on the mineral surface, providing hydride equivalents that reduce CO2 via a two-electron transfer to formate (HCOO-). The reaction is thermodynamically favorable under the highly reducing, alkaline vent conditions.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is a well-established hydrothermal reaction analogous to the Wood-Ljungdahl pathway. Demonstrated by Preiner et al. (2020, Nature Ecology & Evolution) and Herschy et al. (2014), showing that native iron-sulfur minerals catalyze CO2 fixation under simulated alkaline vent conditions. This provides the C1 feedstock for downstream formaldehyde production."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "370-470K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Subseafloor hydrothermal conditions, Fe0 as strong reductant"}, "mechanism": "Formate is further reduced on Fe3O4/Fe0 surfaces through a two-electron reduction that removes one oxygen, yielding formaldehyde (H2CO). Elemental iron provides the driving force for reduction, being oxidized to Fe2+ in the process. Magnetite serves as the catalytic surface facilitating hydrogen transfer.", "reasoning": "Reduction of formate to formaldehyde under hydrothermal conditions is supported by work on serpentinization-driven organic synthesis (McCollom & Seewald, 2007, EPSL; Seewald et al., 2006). Formaldehyde is a critical C1 building block for the formose reaction that produces the C3 sugar precursors needed for the downstream cyanosulfidic valine pathway. This step connects hydrothermal CO2 fixation to surface sugar chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde (formose initiation)", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline conditions (pH 10-11), Ca(OH)2 present, evaporitic pool setting"}, "mechanism": "Two molecules of formaldehyde undergo an aldol-type condensation catalyzed by Ca(OH)2 and clay mineral surfaces. The Cannizzaro reaction provides initial glycolaldehyde through disproportionation, and subsequent aldol addition of formaldehyde to glycolaldehyde creates C3 sugars. Borate minerals stabilize the sugar products against degradation by forming borate esters.", "reasoning": "The formose reaction (Butlerow, 1861) is the classical prebiotic route to sugars from formaldehyde. Ricardo et al. (2004, Science) demonstrated that borate minerals stabilize sugars (especially ribose) against degradation, enabling productive formose chemistry. Montmorillonite clay catalyzes the condensation and concentrates reactants. This produces the glycolaldehyde intermediate needed for C3 sugar synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to dihydroxyacetone (formose chain extension)", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "borate minerals, Ca(OH)2", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline formose conditions, borate stabilization, wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pools"}, "mechanism": "Glycolaldehyde undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde to form glyceraldehyde (C3 aldose), which then isomerizes via a 1,2-hydride shift (Lobry de Bruyn-van Ekenstein rearrangement) to dihydroxyacetone (C3 ketose). Borate complexation stabilizes the triose products and shifts the equilibrium toward the ketose form.", "reasoning": "Formose-type aldol chain extension from glycolaldehyde to C3 sugars is well documented (Breslow, 1959; Orgel, 2000). Borate stabilization of the triose is demonstrated by Ricardo et al. (2004, Science). Dihydroxyacetone is the specific C3 sugar feedstock required for the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic valine pathway."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Glycolaldehyde to hydroxyacetone via formose methylation", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "borate minerals (colemanite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite, borate minerals", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Formose reaction conditions, alternative branching pathway under slightly different pH/concentration"}, "mechanism": "Under formose conditions, glycolaldehyde undergoes retro-aldol/aldol rearrangement with formaldehyde, producing hydroxyacetone (acetol, CH3COCH2OH) as an alternative C3 product alongside dihydroxyacetone. The methyl group of hydroxyacetone arises from dehydration-rearrangement of an intermediate aldol adduct.", "reasoning": "Hydroxyacetone is a known product of the formose reaction alongside dihydroxyacetone and glyceraldehyde (Mizuno & Weiss, 1974). Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry) explicitly use hydroxyacetone as an alternative starting sugar for the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. This provides a second upstream entry point to the acetone hub."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Dihydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu0)", "hydrogen sulfide (H2S)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions: Cu0 as single-electron reductant, H2S as co-reductant, surface evaporitic pool"}, "mechanism": "Copper acts as a single-electron reductant in concert with hydrogen sulfide, stripping both hydroxymethyl groups from dihydroxyacetone and reducing the C3 backbone to acetone. Cu0 is oxidized to Cu+ or Cu2+ during the transformation, while H2S is oxidized to disulfane (H2S2).", "reasoning": "Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this reductive deoxygenation as Step 1 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. Copper and H2S are essential reagents in their unified cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework that converts sugar feedstocks into ketone intermediates suitable for downstream nitrile chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu0)", "hydrogen sulfide (H2S)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions: Cu0 as single-electron reductant, H2S as co-reductant"}, "mechanism": "Copper/H2S-mediated reductive removal of the hydroxyl group from hydroxyacetone (acetol), yielding acetone. The mechanism is analogous to rxn_006 but requires removal of only one hydroxymethyl group.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as an alternative upstream entry to the acetone hub from a different sugar derivative. This provides pathway redundancy: both DHA and hydroxyacetone converge on the same acetone intermediate under identical cyanosulfidic conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Cyanohydrin formation: acetone + HCN", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu0)", "hydrogen sulfide (H2S)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic pool conditions, mildly basic pH favoring CN- nucleophile"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide ion (CN-) to the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of acetone. The cyanide attacks the sp2 carbon, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the tertiary cyanohydrin (acetone cyanohydrin). The symmetrical dimethyl substitution of acetone produces a single cyanohydrin product.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this cyanohydrin formation as Step 2 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. This is a classic Kiliani-type reaction (ketone variant) that introduces the C-CN bond that will ultimately become the carboxylic acid group of valine."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Thioamide formation: cyanohydrin + H2S", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu0)", "hydrogen sulfide (H2S)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions, H2S acts as both reagent and part of the redox environment"}, "mechanism": "H2S adds across the nitrile (C\u2261N) triple bond of the cyanohydrin. The sulfur nucleophile attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, and proton transfer completes the conversion to a thioamide (C(=S)NH2). This activates the nitrile for subsequent reductive chemistry by replacing the strong C\u2261N triple bond with a more reactive thioamide functionality.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 3 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. Thioamide formation is a key step in the cyanosulfidic framework: conversion of nitriles to thioamides via H2S activates the molecule for the critical Cu-mediated reductive rearrangement that builds the branched valine carbon skeleton."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Reductive rearrangement with chain extension (Cu/H2S-mediated)", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015", "mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu0)", "hydrogen sulfide (H2S)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "elemental copper (Cu0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic conditions, Cu0 as single-electron reductant, H2S as co-reductant and sulfur source"}, "mechanism": "This is a complex, multi-step cyanosulfidic transformation. The thioamide undergoes reductive rearrangement mediated by copper and hydrogen sulfide. The thioamide nitrogen is lost, and a new C\u2013C bond is formed by incorporation of a second equivalent of HCN. Elemental copper acts as a single-electron reductant, while H2S provides reducing equivalents and sulfur acts as a leaving group (forming disulfane, H2S2). The net result is chain extension: the C4 thioamide is converted to a C5 alpha-hydroxynitrile with an isopropyl branch, establishing the valine carbon skeleton.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 4 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway \u2014 the critical C\u2013C bond-forming step that builds the branched-chain architecture unique to valine. This is the most mechanistically complex step in the network and represents the key innovation of the cyanosulfidic approach: using Cu/H2S redox chemistry to achieve C-C bond formation through thioamide intermediates."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker-type amination of alpha-hydroxynitrile", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["elemental copper (Cu0)", "hydrogen sulfide (H2S)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "Cyanosulfidic pool, NH3 available from volcanic outgassing or HCN hydrolysis"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic substitution of the alpha-hydroxyl group by ammonia. The OH is displaced by NH3, converting the hydroxynitrile to an aminonitrile. This is a Strecker-type amination step \u2014 the replacement of OH by NH2 at the alpha-carbon adjacent to the nitrile \u2014 producing the direct aminonitrile precursor of valine.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as Step 5 of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. The Strecker-type amination converts the alpha-hydroxynitrile to the aminonitrile, setting up the final hydrolysis to the amino acid. This reaction is well-precedented in prebiotic chemistry (Strecker, 1854; Miller, 1957)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile to L-valine", "inputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_022", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface catalysis)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Hydrolysis in aqueous pool, possibly aided by wet-dry cycling and mild heating"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolysis of the nitrile group of the aminonitrile to the carboxylic acid. Water attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-methylbutanamide), which further hydrolyzes to the free carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. This is the final Strecker-type hydrolysis step that converts the aminonitrile to L-valine.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) demonstrated this as the final step (Step 6) of the cyanosulfidic valine pathway. Nitrile hydrolysis to carboxylic acids is thermodynamically favorable and kinetically accessible under mild aqueous conditions, especially with clay mineral catalysis (Ferris et al., 1996)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile to L-valine (Pathway 2)", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_022", "mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay surface catalysis)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Hydrolysis with concomitant chain shortening, aqueous pool conditions"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolysis of the nitrile group of the C6 aminonitrile with concomitant loss of one carbon (chain shortening), converting the C6 aminonitrile to the C5 amino acid valine. The chain shortening may occur through a retro-aldol or decarboxylative mechanism under the cyanosulfidic conditions, releasing one CH2 unit as formaldehyde or CO2.", "reasoning": "Patel et al. (2015, Nature Chemistry, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) described this as an alternative route to valine from the C6 aminonitrile produced through the hydroxyacetone branch of the cyanosulfidic network. The chain-shortening mechanism remains an open question in the literature."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_021", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_019"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (>100 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis at black smoker or subseafloor hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Carbon monoxide and hydrogen gas undergo Fischer-Tropsch-type (FTT) synthesis on magnetite surfaces, producing a mixture of hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes. Isobutyraldehyde (2-methylpropanal) is a branched C4 aldehyde product formed through chain growth and branching on the mineral surface. CO adsorbs dissociatively, and sequential hydrogenation/chain growth steps build the branched carbon skeleton.", "reasoning": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of aldehydes and hydrocarbons on magnetite under hydrothermal conditions was demonstrated by McCollom et al. (1999, EPSL) and Rushdi & Simoneit (2001). Branched aldehydes including isobutyraldehyde are plausible products of FTT synthesis, providing a hydrothermal route to the Strecker aldehyde precursor of valine."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Classical Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_019", "mol_004", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_003"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Strecker conditions: aldehyde + NH3 + HCN in aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "Classical Strecker synthesis: (1) Ammonia attacks the aldehyde carbonyl of isobutyraldehyde to form a hemiaminal, which dehydrates to an imine (Schiff base). (2) Cyanide ion (CN-) then adds to the electrophilic imine carbon in a nucleophilic addition, yielding 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile \u2014 the same aminonitrile produced by the cyanosulfidic pathway. This provides a direct, well-characterized route from a branched aldehyde to the valine aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is one of the oldest and most established prebiotic amino acid syntheses (Strecker, 1854; Miller, 1953). Miller's spark discharge experiments demonstrated that branched-chain amino acids including valine are produced via Strecker chemistry from aldehydes generated in the reducing atmosphere. The use of isobutyraldehyde as the specific aldehyde precursor for valine Strecker synthesis is described in standard prebiotic chemistry references (Miller & Orgel, 1974)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine", "inputs": ["mol_020", "mol_006", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_022", "mol_003"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2), mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent conditions, FeS/FeS2 surface catalysis, NH3 from vent fluids"}, "mechanism": "Reductive amination of the alpha-keto acid on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces. The carbonyl oxygen of alpha-ketoisovalerate is attacked by ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base), which is then reduced by H2 or FeS-derived electrons to yield L-valine. The iron-sulfur mineral surface provides both the catalytic site and the reducing equivalents for imine reduction.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-keto acids on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces is supported by the work of Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Letters) and Barge et al. (2019, PNAS), who demonstrated amino acid synthesis from keto acids and ammonia under hydrothermal conditions. This provides a direct hydrothermal route to valine that bypasses the surface cyanosulfidic pathway entirely, representing an alternative environmental context for valine formation."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Hydrothermal synthesis of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and formaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_020"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4), magnetite (Fe3O4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "Multi-step process: CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite, then aldol with formaldehyde and reduction/dehydration"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-ketoisovalerate is synthesized through a multi-step process on iron-sulfur mineral surfaces: (1) CO2 is reduced to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite surfaces (analogous to reductive TCA cycle intermediates). (2) Pyruvate undergoes aldol condensation with formaldehyde and a second carbon unit, followed by reduction and dehydration/rearrangement to yield the branched C5 alpha-keto acid. The mineral surfaces template the carbon-carbon bond-forming steps.", "reasoning": "This reaction is partially speculative but grounded in demonstrated hydrothermal CO2 fixation to pyruvate (Cody et al., 2000, Science; Varma et al., 2018, Nature Ecology & Evolution) and the general principle that alpha-keto acids are central hubs of prebiotic metabolism. The specific construction of the branched C5 skeleton from C1/C3 units on mineral surfaces extends the demonstrated chemistry of CO2 fixation on iron-sulfur minerals. This step is necessary to connect the hydrothermal reductive amination route (rxn_016) to the upstream feedstock network."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Full Hydrothermal-to-Surface Cyanosulfidic Route via DHA", "description": "Complete pathway from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through formose sugar synthesis to cyanosulfidic valine production via dihydroxyacetone. Represents the most complete environmental interconnection from deep-sea vent CO2 to surface amino acid.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_015", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Full Hydrothermal-to-Surface Cyanosulfidic Route via Hydroxyacetone", "description": "Complete pathway from hydrothermal CO2 fixation through formose chemistry to cyanosulfidic valine production via hydroxyacetone. Parallels P1 but uses the alternative C3 sugar feedstock.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_005", "rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_011", "mol_012", "mol_015", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Surface-only Cyanosulfidic Route from Dihydroxyacetone", "description": "The primary Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway starting from dihydroxyacetone assumed available in surface pools. Six-step sequence: reductive deoxygenation, cyanohydrin formation, thioamide formation, reductive rearrangement, amination, hydrolysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Surface-only Cyanosulfidic Route from Hydroxyacetone", "description": "The parallel Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic pathway starting from hydroxyacetone. Converges with P3 at the acetone hub.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Cyanosulfidic Pathway 2 via C6 Aminonitrile (from DHA)", "description": "Alternative cyanosulfidic route that produces valine from the C6 aminonitrile (2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile) through hydrolysis with chain shortening. Upstream uses DHA route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Cyanosulfidic Pathway 2 via C6 Aminonitrile (from Hydroxyacetone)", "description": "Alternative cyanosulfidic route via C6 aminonitrile using hydroxyacetone as the upstream sugar feedstock.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013", "mol_014", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch to Surface Strecker Route", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde produced by hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite undergoes classical Strecker synthesis with HCN and NH3 in surface pools, converging at the aminonitrile hub before hydrolysis to valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_014", "rxn_015", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_019", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal Reductive Amination Route", "description": "Direct hydrothermal route: alpha-ketoisovalerate synthesized on iron-sulfur minerals undergoes reductive amination with ammonia on pyrite/mackinawite surfaces to yield valine. Entirely hydrothermal, bypassing surface chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_017", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Full CO2-to-Valine Hydrothermal Reductive Amination", "description": "Complete hydrothermal pathway from CO2 through formate, formaldehyde, and alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine via reductive amination. Represents the deepest hydrothermal route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_017", "rxn_016"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_020"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Hybrid Hydrothermal-Surface Route: Formaldehyde to Strecker via Formose", "description": "Hydrothermal formaldehyde feeds formose chemistry producing glycolaldehyde and DHA in surface pools, with DHA entering the cyanosulfidic pathway. This traces the longest environmental interconnection chain.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_016"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_008", "mol_012", "mol_004", "mol_015", "mol_016"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_008", "description": "Formaldehyde \u2014 Central C1 hub connecting hydrothermal CO2 fixation to surface formose chemistry", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_017"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Acetone \u2014 Key convergence point where two sugar feedstocks (DHA and hydroxyacetone) merge before entering the nitrile-based skeleton assembly", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_004", "description": "Hydrogen cyanide \u2014 Essential C1 nitrogen source used in cyanohydrin formation, reductive chain extension, and Strecker synthesis", "incoming_reactions": [], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_008", "rxn_010", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_015", "description": "2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile \u2014 Convergence point containing the complete C5 branched valine skeleton, feeding into both C5 aminonitrile (amination) and C6 aminonitrile routes", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_010"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_011"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_016", "description": "2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile \u2014 Final aminonitrile convergence point reached by both the cyanosulfidic pathway (via amination) and the Strecker route (from isobutyraldehyde)", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_015"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_012"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 408646.53182029724, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T04:36:17.605106", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.8\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: L-Valine\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network constructs L-valine through multiple convergent prebiotic routes anchored in the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework. The primary pathway proceeds from C3 sugar derivatives (dihydroxyacetone, hydroxyacetone) through reductive deoxygenation to acetone (a central hub), followed by cyanohydrin formation, thioamide conversion, Cu/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement with chain extension, Strecker-type amination, and nitrile hydrolysis. Upstream hydrothermal chemistry provides C1 feedstocks (formate, formaldehyde) via CO2 reduction on iron-sulfur minerals, which feed into surface formose chemistry to generate the C3 sugar precursors. A parallel Strecker route via isobutyraldehyde (from Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis) and a hydrothermal reductive amination route via alpha-ketoisovalerate provide alternative environmental pathways to valine. The network features five hub molecules (formaldehyde, acetone, HCN, 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile, and 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile) creating dense interconnection and redundancy across hydrothermal, surface, and biochemical environments.\n\nMOLECULES (22 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (Carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (Hydrogen gas) [starting]\n  - mol_003: H2O (Water) [starting]\n  - mol_004: CHN (Hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: H2S (Hydrogen sulfide) [starting]\n  - mol_006: H3N (Ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_007: CHO (Formate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CH2O (Formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C2H4O2 (Glycolaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C3H6O3 (Dihydroxyacetone) [intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C3H6O2 (Hydroxyacetone) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: C3H6O (Acetone) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C4H7NO (Acetone cyanohydrin) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H9NOS (2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C5H9NO (2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C5H10N2 (2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_017: C6H12N2 (2-Amino-4-methylpentanenitrile) [intermediate]\n  - mol_018: H2S2 (Disulfane) [intermediate]\n  - mol_019: C4H8O (Isobutyraldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_020: C5H8O3 (alpha-Ketoisovalerate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_021: CO (Carbon monoxide) [starting]\n  - mol_022: C5H11NO2 (L-Valine) [target]\n\nREACTIONS (17 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (CO2 reduction to formate on greigite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_007, mol_002 -> mol_008 (Formate reduction to formaldehyde on magnetite) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_008, mol_008 -> mol_009 (Formaldehyde self-condensation to glycolaldehyde (formose initiation)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_004: mol_009, mol_008 -> mol_010 (Glycolaldehyde + formaldehyde to dihydroxyacetone (formose chain extension)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_005: mol_009, mol_008 -> mol_011 (Glycolaldehyde to hydroxyacetone via formose methylation) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_010, mol_005 -> mol_012, mol_003 (Dihydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_011, mol_005 -> mol_012, mol_003 (Hydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation to acetone) [Surface]\n  - rxn_008: mol_012, mol_004 -> mol_013 (Cyanohydrin formation: acetone + HCN) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_013, mol_005 -> mol_014 (Thioamide formation: cyanohydrin + H2S) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_014, mol_004, mol_005, mol_003 -> mol_015, mol_018 (Reductive rearrangement with chain extension (Cu/H2S-mediated)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_011: mol_015, mol_006 -> mol_016, mol_003 (Strecker-type amination of alpha-hydroxynitrile) [Surface]\n  - rxn_012: mol_016, mol_003 -> mol_022, mol_006 (Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile to L-valine) [Surface]\n  - rxn_013: mol_017, mol_003 -> mol_022, mol_006 (Nitrile hydrolysis of 2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile to L-valine (Pathway 2)) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_021, mol_002 -> mol_019 (Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_015: mol_019, mol_004, mol_006 -> mol_016, mol_003 (Classical Strecker synthesis of valine aminonitrile from isobutyraldehyde) [Surface]\n  - rxn_016: mol_020, mol_006, mol_002 -> mol_022, mol_003 (Hydrothermal reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate to valine) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_017: mol_008, mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_020 (Hydrothermal synthesis of alpha-ketoisovalerate from pyruvate and formaldehyde) [Hydrothermal]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Full Hydrothermal-to-Surface Cyanosulfidic Route via DHA (10 steps)\n  - P2: Full Hydrothermal-to-Surface Cyanosulfidic Route via Hydroxyacetone (10 steps)\n  - P3: Surface-only Cyanosulfidic Route from Dihydroxyacetone (6 steps)\n  - P4: Surface-only Cyanosulfidic Route from Hydroxyacetone (6 steps)\n  - P5: Cyanosulfidic Pathway 2 via C6 Aminonitrile (from DHA) (5 steps)\n  - P6: Cyanosulfidic Pathway 2 via C6 Aminonitrile (from Hydroxyacetone) (5 steps)\n  - P7: Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch to Surface Strecker Route (3 steps)\n  - P8: Hydrothermal Reductive Amination Route (3 steps)\n  - P9: Full CO2-to-Valine Hydrothermal Reductive Amination (4 steps)\n  - P10: Hybrid Hydrothermal-Surface Route: Formaldehyde to Strecker via Formose (10 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_008, mol_012, mol_004, mol_015, mol_016\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 5\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n# Prebiotic Synthesis of L-Valine: Comprehensive Literature Review\n\n## 1. Known Prebiotic Synthesis Routes\n\nTwo experimentally demonstrated pathways produce L-valine (C5H11NO2, SMILES: CC(C)C(C(=O)O)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)) from prebiotically available precursors. Both operate within the cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework under surface environment conditions.\n\n### Pathway 1: Cyanosulfidic Protometabolism via Dihydroxyacetone (Surface Environment)\n\nThe cyanosulfidic protometabolism pathway demonstrated by Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202) constructs L-valine through a 6-step sequence starting from dihydroxyacetone, proceeding through acetone and a series of nitrile intermediates. This pathway follows the general cyanosulfidic strategy: sugar-derived ketones undergo cyanohydrin formation, thioamide conversion, reductive rearrangement with copper/H2S, amination, and final nitrile hydrolysis to the amino acid.\n\n**Step 1**: Dihydroxyacetone \u2192 Acetone + 2 H2O (Reductive deoxygenation)\n- SMILES: O=C(CO)CO>>CC(C)=O.O.O\n- Reactants: Dihydroxyacetone (C3H6O3, SMILES: C(C(=O)CO)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2, MW: 90.08)\n- Products: Acetone (C3H6O, SMILES: CC(=O)C, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3, MW: 58.08) + H2O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: **Sulfidic acid** (H2S, SMILES: S) and **Elemental copper** ([Cu]) as solutes\n- Mechanism: Reductive deoxygenation of the triose sugar dihydroxyacetone (DHA) under cyanosulfidic conditions. Copper acts as a single-electron reductant in concert with hydrogen sulfide, stripping the hydroxymethyl groups and reducing the C3 backbone to acetone. This converts a sugar feedstock into a simple ketone suitable for downstream cyanohydrin chemistry. The reaction is analogous to the broader Patel et al. demonstration that cyanosulfidic chemistry can interconvert sugars and metabolic intermediates.\n\n**Step 2**: Acetone + Hydrogen cyanide \u2192 Acetone cyanohydrin (Cyanohydrin formation)\n- SMILES: CC(C)=O.C#N>>CC(C)(O)C#N\n- Reactants: Acetone (C3H6O, SMILES: CC(=O)C) + Hydrogen cyanide (CHN, SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H, MW: 27.03)\n- Products: Acetone cyanohydrin (C4H7NO, SMILES: CC(C)(C#N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NO/c1-4(2,6)3-5/h6H,1-2H3, MW: 85.10)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide (CN\u207b) to the carbonyl carbon of acetone. The cyanide ion attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon, and subsequent protonation of the resulting alkoxide yields the cyanohydrin. This is a classic cyanohydrin reaction \u2014 the ketone form of the Kiliani reaction \u2014 producing a tertiary cyanohydrin due to the symmetrical dimethyl substitution of acetone.\n\n**Step 3**: Acetone cyanohydrin + Hydrogen sulfide \u2192 2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide (Thioamide formation)\n- SMILES: CC(C)(O)C#N.S>>CC(C)(O)C(N)=S\n- Reactants: Acetone cyanohydrin (C4H7NO, SMILES: CC(C)(C#N)O) + Hydrogen sulfide (H2S, SMILES: S, InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2, MW: 34.08)\n- Products: 2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide (C4H9NOS, SMILES: CC(C)(C(=S)N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NOS/c1-4(2,6)3(5)7/h6H,1-2H3,(H2,5,7), MW: 119.19)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: H2S adds across the nitrile (C\u2261N) triple bond of the cyanohydrin. The sulfur nucleophile attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, and proton transfer completes the conversion to a thioamide (C(=S)NH2). This is a key step in the cyanosulfidic framework: conversion of nitriles to thioamides via H2S, which activates the nitrile for subsequent reductive chemistry.\n\n**Step 4**: 2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide + HCN + H2S + H2O \u2192 2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile + Disulfane + H2S (Reductive cyanide-mediated rearrangement)\n- SMILES: CC(C)(O)C(N)=S.C#N.S.S.O>>CC(C)C(O)C#N.SS.SS.S\n- Reactants: 2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide (C4H9NOS) + HCN (CHN) + H2S (H2S) + H2O\n- Products: 2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile (C5H9NO, SMILES: CC(C)C(C#N)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-4(2)5(7)3-6/h4-5,7H,1-2H3, MW: 99.13) + Disulfane (H2S2, SMILES: SS, InChI: InChI=1S/H2S2/c1-2/h1-2H, MW: 66.15) + H2S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: **Sulfidic acid** (H2S, SMILES: S) and **Elemental copper** ([Cu]) as solutes\n- Mechanism: This is a complex, multi-step cyanosulfidic transformation. The thioamide undergoes reductive rearrangement mediated by copper and hydrogen sulfide. The thioamide nitrogen is lost, and a new C\u2013C bond is formed by incorporation of the second equivalent of HCN. Elemental copper acts as a single-electron reductant, while H2S provides reducing equivalents and sulfur acts as a leaving group (forming disulfane, H2S2). The net result is chain extension: the C4 thioamide is converted to a C5 \u03b1-hydroxynitrile with an isopropyl branch, establishing the valine carbon skeleton. This rearrangement is the critical C\u2013C bond-forming step that builds the branched-chain architecture unique to valine.\n\n**Step 5**: 2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile + Ammonia \u2192 2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile + H2O (Amination)\n- SMILES: CC(C)C(O)C#N.N>>CC(C)C(N)C#N.O\n- Reactants: 2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile (C5H9NO) + Ammonia (H3N, SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3, MW: 17.03)\n- Products: 2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (C5H10N2, SMILES: CC(C)C(C#N)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(7)3-6/h4-5H,7H2,1-2H3, MW: 98.15) + H2O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic substitution of the hydroxyl group by ammonia. The \u03b1-hydroxy group is displaced by NH3, converting the hydroxynitrile to an aminonitrile. This is a Strecker-type amination step \u2014 the replacement of OH by NH2 at the \u03b1-carbon adjacent to the nitrile \u2014 producing the direct aminonitrile precursor of valine.\n\n**Step 6**: 2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Valine + NH3 (Nitrile hydrolysis)\n- SMILES: CC(C)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(C)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Reactants: 2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (C5H10N2) + 2 H2O\n- Products: L-Valine (C5H11NO2, SMILES: CC(C)C(C(=O)O)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8), MW: 117.15) + Ammonia (NH3)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Hydrolysis of the nitrile group of the aminonitrile to the carboxylic acid. Water attacks the electrophilic nitrile carbon, forming an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-methylbutanamide), which further hydrolyzes to the free carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. This is the final Strecker-type hydrolysis step that converts the aminonitrile to the amino acid L-valine.\n\n### Pathway 2: Cyanosulfidic Protometabolism via Hydroxyacetone (Surface Environment)\n\nA parallel pathway in the same Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic system starts from **hydroxyacetone** instead of dihydroxyacetone. This converges on the same target (L-valine) but proceeds through a C6 aminonitrile intermediate (2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile), suggesting the cyanosulfidic network produces valine through multiple convergent routes.\n\n**Step 1**: Hydroxyacetone \u2192 Acetone + H2O (Reductive deoxygenation)\n- SMILES: CC(=O)CO.>>CC(C)=O.O\n- Reactants: Hydroxyacetone (C3H6O2, SMILES: CC(=O)CO, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h4H,2H2,1H3, MW: 74.08)\n- Products: Acetone (C3H6O, SMILES: CC(=O)C) + H2O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: **Sulfidic acid** (H2S, SMILES: S) and **Elemental copper** ([Cu]) as solutes\n- Mechanism: Reductive deoxygenation of hydroxyacetone (acetol) mediated by copper and hydrogen sulfide under cyanosulfidic conditions. The hydroxymethyl group (\u2013CH2OH) is reduced, removing the oxygen to produce the simpler ketone (acetone). This provides an alternative upstream entry point to the acetone intermediate from a different sugar derivative.\n\n**Step 2**: 2-Amino-4-methylpentanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Valine + NH3 (Nitrile hydrolysis)\n- SMILES: CC(C)CC(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(C)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Reactants: 2-Amino-4-methylpentanenitrile (C6H12N2, SMILES: CC(C)CC(C#N)N, InChI: InChI=1S/C6H12N2/c1-5(2)3-6(8)4-7/h5-6H,3,8H2,1-2H3, MW: 112.17) + 2 H2O\n- Products: L-Valine (C5H11NO2, SMILES: CC(C)C(C(=O)O)N) + Ammonia (NH3)\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Mechanism: Hydrolysis of the nitrile group of the C6 aminonitrile. Notably, this reaction involves both nitrile hydrolysis and loss of one carbon (decarboxylation or equivalent chain shortening), converting a C6 aminonitrile to the C5 amino acid valine. Water attacks the nitrile carbon, forming the carboxylic acid with release of ammonia. The net loss of one CH2 unit during hydrolysis may occur through a retro-aldol or decarboxylative mechanism under the cyanosulfidic conditions.\n\n## 2. Key Intermediates and Precursors\n\n### Hub Molecule: Acetone (C3H6O)\n- Formula: C3H6O\n- SMILES: CC(=O)C\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3\n- MW: 58.08\n- Role: **Central convergence point** \u2014 acetone is produced by two independent upstream reactions (reductive deoxygenation of dihydroxyacetone and of hydroxyacetone) and consumed by the cyanohydrin reaction that initiates the valine carbon skeleton assembly. It is the key branch-point where multiple sugar-derived feedstocks converge before entering the nitrile-based pathway to valine.\n\n### Key Intermediates\n\n**Acetone cyanohydrin** (C4H7NO)\n- Formula: C4H7NO\n- SMILES: CC(C)(C#N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H7NO/c1-4(2,6)3-5/h6H,1-2H3\n- MW: 85.10\n- Role: First nitrile intermediate \u2014 formed by HCN addition to acetone, carries the initial C\u2013CN bond that will become the carboxylic acid of valine\n\n**2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide** (C4H9NOS)\n- Formula: C4H9NOS\n- SMILES: CC(C)(C(=S)N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C4H9NOS/c1-4(2,6)3(5)7/h6H,1-2H3,(H2,5,7)\n- MW: 119.19\n- Role: Thioamide intermediate \u2014 the H2S-activated form of the cyanohydrin that undergoes copper-mediated reductive rearrangement to build the branched C5 skeleton\n\n**2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile** (C5H9NO)\n- Formula: C5H9NO\n- SMILES: CC(C)C(C#N)O\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H9NO/c1-4(2)5(7)3-6/h4-5,7H,1-2H3\n- MW: 99.13\n- Role: \u03b1-Hydroxynitrile intermediate \u2014 contains the full valine carbon skeleton (C5, branched) with a hydroxyl group that will be replaced by an amine\n\n**2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile** (C5H10N2)\n- Formula: C5H10N2\n- SMILES: CC(C)C(C#N)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-4(2)5(7)3-6/h4-5H,7H2,1-2H3\n- MW: 98.15\n- Role: **Direct aminonitrile precursor of valine** \u2014 the Strecker aminonitrile that hydrolyzes to L-valine. This is a key convergence point as it is the last intermediate before the final hydrolysis step.\n\n**2-Amino-4-methylpentanenitrile** (C6H12N2)\n- Formula: C6H12N2\n- SMILES: CC(C)CC(C#N)N\n- InChI: InChI=1S/C6H12N2/c1-5(2)3-6(8)4-7/h5-6H,3,8H2,1-2H3\n- MW: 112.17\n- Role: Alternative aminonitrile \u2014 a C6 aminonitrile from Pathway 2 that also hydrolyzes to valine (with chain shortening)\n\n**Disulfane** (H2S2)\n- Formula: H2S2\n- SMILES: SS\n- InChI: InChI=1S/H2S2/c1-2/h1-2H\n- MW: 66.15\n- Role: Byproduct of the copper/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement (Step 4 of Pathway 1)\n\n### Starting Molecules\n- **H2O**: SMILES: O, InChI: InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\n- **HCN** (hydrogen cyanide): SMILES: C#N, InChI: InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\n- **H2S** (hydrogen sulfide): SMILES: S, InChI: InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\n- **NH3** (ammonia): SMILES: N, InChI: InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\n- **Dihydroxyacetone**: SMILES: C(C(=O)CO)O, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O3/c4-1-3(6)2-5/h4-5H,1-2H2\n- **Hydroxyacetone**: SMILES: CC(=O)CO, InChI: InChI=1S/C3H6O2/c1-3(5)2-4/h4H,2H2,1H3\n\n## 3. Reaction Mechanisms and Conditions\n\n### Reactions Producing Acetone (Upstream Hub)\n\n**Reaction U1: Dihydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation (Cu/H2S-mediated)**\n- Dihydroxyacetone \u2192 Acetone + 2 H2O\n- SMILES: O=C(CO)CO>>CC(C)=O.O.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: Sulfidic acid (H2S) + Elemental copper ([Cu])\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Copper/H2S-mediated reductive removal of both hydroxyl groups from the triose sugar dihydroxyacetone, yielding acetone.\n\n**Reaction U2: Hydroxyacetone reductive deoxygenation (Cu/H2S-mediated)**\n- Hydroxyacetone \u2192 Acetone + H2O\n- SMILES: CC(=O)CO.>>CC(C)=O.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: Sulfidic acid (H2S) + Elemental copper ([Cu])\n- Source: Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Copper/H2S-mediated reductive removal of the hydroxyl group from hydroxyacetone (acetol), yielding acetone.\n\n### Reactions Building the Valine Carbon Skeleton (Middle Steps)\n\n**Reaction M1: Cyanohydrin formation**\n- Acetone + HCN \u2192 Acetone cyanohydrin\n- SMILES: CC(C)=O.C#N>>CC(C)(O)C#N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel et al. (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to the carbonyl of acetone, forming a tertiary cyanohydrin.\n\n**Reaction M2: Thioamide formation**\n- Acetone cyanohydrin + H2S \u2192 2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide\n- SMILES: CC(C)(O)C#N.S>>CC(C)(O)C(N)=S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel et al. (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: H2S addition across the nitrile triple bond, converting the cyanohydrin to a thioamide.\n\n**Reaction M3: Reductive rearrangement (chain extension)**\n- 2-Hydroxy-2-methylpropanethioamide + HCN + H2S + H2O \u2192 2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile + Disulfane + H2S\n- SMILES: CC(C)(O)C(N)=S.C#N.S.S.O>>CC(C)C(O)C#N.SS.SS.S\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Agents: Sulfidic acid (H2S) + Elemental copper ([Cu])\n- Source: Patel et al. (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Cu/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement incorporating a second HCN unit. The thioamide is reductively cleaved, and a new C\u2013C bond is formed with HCN, building the branched C5 skeleton. Disulfane (H2S2) is a byproduct of the sulfur-mediated redox chemistry.\n\n**Reaction M4: Amination (Strecker-type)**\n- 2-Hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile + NH3 \u2192 2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile + H2O\n- SMILES: CC(C)C(O)C#N.N>>CC(C)C(N)C#N.O\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel et al. (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Nucleophilic substitution of the \u03b1-hydroxyl group by ammonia, converting the hydroxynitrile to the aminonitrile.\n\n### Reactions Producing L-Valine (Final Steps)\n\n**Reaction F1: Nitrile hydrolysis (from C5 aminonitrile)**\n- 2-Amino-3-methylbutanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Valine + NH3\n- SMILES: CC(C)C(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(C)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel et al. (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Hydrolysis of the nitrile to carboxylic acid via amide intermediate, with release of ammonia.\n\n**Reaction F2: Nitrile hydrolysis (from C6 aminonitrile)**\n- 2-Amino-4-methylpentanenitrile + 2 H2O \u2192 L-Valine + NH3\n- SMILES: CC(C)CC(N)C#N.O.O>>CC(C)C(N)C(=O)O.N\n- Environment: Surface (cyanosulfidic conditions)\n- Source: Patel et al. (2015), *Nature Chemistry*, DOI: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- Mechanism: Hydrolysis of the C6 aminonitrile nitrile group with concomitant chain shortening to yield the C5 amino acid valine.\n\n## 4. Mineral Catalysts and Surfaces\n\nThe following catalytic agents are experimentally documented for L-valine synthesis reactions in the cyanosulfidic protometabolism framework:\n\n- **Elemental copper (Cu\u2070)**: Metallic copper acts as a single-electron reductant in the cyanosulfidic system. It mediates the reductive deoxygenation of sugar-derived molecules (dihydroxyacetone \u2192 acetone, hydroxyacetone \u2192 acetone) and the reductive rearrangement of thioamides (chain extension step). Copper is oxidized to Cu\u207a or Cu\u00b2\u207a during these transformations. Patel et al. (2015) demonstrated that elemental copper is essential for the reductive steps in the cyanosulfidic network.\n\n- **Sulfidic acid (H2S, hydrogen sulfide)**: H2S plays dual roles \u2014 as a reagent (converting nitriles to thioamides, Step 3) and as a co-reductant with copper in the reductive transformations (Steps 1, 4, 7). In the cyanosulfidic framework, H2S is the sulfur source that gives the chemistry its name. It is oxidized to disulfane (H2S2, SMILES: SS) during reductive steps. H2S is prebiotically available from volcanic outgassing and hydrothermal emissions.\n\nNote: Unlike hydrothermal pathways that use iron-sulfur minerals (greigite, pyrite, magnetite), the valine synthesis pathway operates entirely within the surface cyanosulfidic framework using dissolved copper and H2S as solute agents rather than mineral surfaces.\n\n## 5. Experimental Evidence\n\n### Study 1: Patel et al. (2015)\n- **Title**: \"Common origins of RNA, protein and lipid precursors in a cyanosulfidic protometabolism\"\n- **Journal**: Nature Chemistry\n- **DOI**: 10.1038/nchem.2202\n- **Authors**: Patel B, Percivalle C, Ritson D, Duffy C, Sutherland J\n- **Key finding**: Demonstrated that a unified cyanosulfidic chemistry network starting from hydrogen cyanide (HCN), hydrogen sulfide (H2S), and simple feedstocks (water, ammonia, phosphate) can produce precursors to all three major classes of biomolecules: RNA nucleotides, amino acids (including valine), and lipid precursors. The chemistry operates under surface conditions (UV irradiation, wet-dry cycles in evaporitic pools) with copper and H2S as key redox agents. For valine specifically, the pathway proceeds through: (1) reductive deoxygenation of sugar derivatives (dihydroxyacetone or hydroxyacetone) to acetone using Cu/H2S; (2) cyanohydrin formation with HCN; (3) thioamide conversion with H2S; (4) Cu/H2S-mediated reductive rearrangement with chain extension by a second HCN unit; (5) amination with ammonia; and (6) final nitrile hydrolysis to the amino acid. This establishes that branched-chain amino acids like valine arise naturally from the same cyanosulfidic chemistry that produces simpler amino acids like glycine and alanine, through the incorporation of ketone (rather than aldehyde) substrates.\n\n## 6. Environmental Context\n\n### Surface Environment (Primary \u2014 Cyanosulfidic Pools)\nAll experimentally demonstrated valine synthesis routes operate under surface cyanosulfidic conditions:\n- **Cyanosulfidic protometabolism** (Patel et al., 2015): The entire valine synthesis network operates in surface evaporitic pools where HCN and H2S are available from atmospheric and volcanic sources. UV irradiation drives certain photochemical steps in the broader cyanosulfidic network (though the specific valine reactions may not require UV directly). Wet-dry cycling in geothermal surface pools concentrates reactants and drives dehydration steps.\n- **Temperature**: Ambient to mildly elevated (300-370 K), characteristic of surface geothermal environments.\n- **Key reagents**: HCN (from atmospheric chemistry, volcanic outgassing), H2S (from volcanic emissions), Cu (from mineral dissolution), NH3 (from atmospheric/volcanic sources), sugar derivatives (dihydroxyacetone, hydroxyacetone \u2014 from formose-type chemistry or photochemical synthesis).\n\n### Hydrothermal Connection\nWhile the valine pathway itself operates under surface conditions, the upstream sugar feedstocks (dihydroxyacetone, hydroxyacetone) could originate from formose-type chemistry in hydrothermal settings or from serpentinization-driven synthesis of formaldehyde (H2CO), which undergoes aldol condensation to form C3 sugars. This provides a potential hydrothermal \u2192 surface flow of carbon feedstocks.\n\n### Environmental Interconnection\n1. **Hydrothermal \u2192 Surface**: Simple C1 molecules (H2CO, HCN) and C3 sugar derivatives produced at hydrothermal vents or by volcanic outgassing are transported to surface pools where cyanosulfidic chemistry operates.\n2. **Surface \u2192 Biochemical**: L-valine produced in surface cyanosulfidic pools enters the prebiotic amino acid pool available for peptide bond formation and proto-metabolic assembly. Valine is one of the 20 canonical amino acids and a key hydrophobic residue in proteins.\n\n## 7. Open Questions and Challenges\n\n1. **Chirality**: The cyanosulfidic pathway produces racemic valine (equal L and D). The origin of homochirality (biological preference for L-amino acids) remains unresolved for valine. Enantiomeric enrichment mechanisms such as asymmetric adsorption on chiral mineral surfaces, circularly polarized light, or amplification through crystal-liquid equilibria have been proposed but not demonstrated specifically for valine.\n\n2. **Acetone availability**: The pathway requires acetone, which is produced by reductive deoxygenation of sugar derivatives (dihydroxyacetone, hydroxyacetone). The prebiotic availability of these C3 sugars depends on the formose reaction or alternative sugar synthesis routes, whose efficiency and selectivity under prebiotic conditions are debated.\n\n3. **Copper availability**: Elemental copper (Cu\u2070) is essential for the reductive steps. While copper minerals exist in early Earth geological settings, the concentration and bioavailability of dissolved Cu\u2070 in prebiotic surface pools needs quantitative constraints. Copper could be released from sulfide minerals (e.g., chalcopyrite) under the acidic or reducing conditions of cyanosulfidic environments.\n\n4. **Selectivity**: The cyanosulfidic network produces many products simultaneously (amino acids, nucleotide precursors, lipid precursors). The selectivity and yield for valine specifically, versus competing products like leucine (from the C6 aminonitrile pathway) or other branched-chain amino acids, needs further quantification.\n\n5. **Chain extension mechanism**: The reductive rearrangement step (Step 4 of Pathway 1) involving Cu/H2S-mediated chain extension through thioamide intermediates is mechanistically complex and not fully characterized at the molecular level. The detailed radical or polar mechanism of the C\u2013C bond formation during this step remains an active area of study.\n\n6. **Pathway 2 chain shortening**: The conversion of the C6 aminonitrile (2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile) to C5 valine involves apparent loss of one carbon during hydrolysis. The mechanism of this chain shortening \u2014 whether through retro-aldol, decarboxylation, or another process \u2014 needs clarification.\n\n=== END CURATED LITERATURE REVIEW ===\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"<id>\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\"rxn_001\": 0.85, ...},\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"environmental_progression\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"target_achievement\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n            \"feedback\": \"<pathway-specific feedback>\",\n            \"approved\": <true if confidence >= 0.8>,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_ids with issues\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"improvements\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"<id of best pathway>\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"<overall assessment>\",\n    \"approved\": <true if any pathway approved>,\n    \"hub_quality\": <0.0-1.0>,\n    \"convergence_quality\": <0.0-1.0>\n}\n", "raw_response": "{\n    \"pathway_evaluations\": [\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.80,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.78,\n                