to surface. This represents a legitimate alternative prebiotic pathway but with lower confidence than the cyanosulfidic route.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify mineral catalyst for FTT (e.g., iron-nickel alloys, awaruite)\", \"Address selectivity concerns for branched aldehyde production\", \"Consider adding intermediate steps between CO/H2 and isobutyraldehyde\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.70\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.65,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.55,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.60,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.65,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.60,\n            \"feedback\": \"Minimal pathway requiring \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (mol_020) as input, with no clear upstream route specified in this pathway alone. The reductive amination (rxn_016) is chemically plausible under hydrothermal conditions but the availability of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate is the bottleneck. The pathway is too short and depends on an intermediate whose prebiotic synthesis is not well established.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_016\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Must be evaluated in context of P9 which provides upstream chemistry\", \"Specify mineral catalyst for hydrothermal reductive amination\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_002\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.45,\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.70\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.55,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.65,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.60,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.58,\n