ce formose to cyanosulfidic amino acid synthesis.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Same improvements as P1\"]\n        }\n    ],\n    \"best_pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n    \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n    \"network_feedback\": \"This is a well-constructed synthesis network for L-valine that is strongly anchored in the Patel et al. (2015) cyanosulfidic protometabolism literature. The core strength lies in pathways P1-P4 and P10, which faithfully reproduce the experimentally demonstrated cyanosulfidic route with appropriate upstream hydrothermal feedstock chemistry. The five hub molecules create meaningful convergence points, and the network correctly identifies acetone as the critical branch-point intermediate. Key strengths: (1) Direct alignment with Patel et al. experimental work; (2) Multiple convergent routes providing redundancy; (3) Good hydrothermal-to-surface environmental flow; (4) Chemically sound core reactions. Key weaknesses: (1) mol_017 (2-amino-4-methylpentanenitrile) is an orphan node with no production reaction, breaking pathways P5 and P6; (2) rxn_017 (formaldehyde + CO2 + H2 \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is a single-step leap with no prebiotic precedent, undermining P9; (3) Surface formose reactions (rxn_003-005) should specify mineral catalysts; (4) Cu is not explicitly listed as an agent in the reaction descriptions for rxn_006, rxn_007, and rxn_010, despite being essential per the literature; (5) No biochemical environment stage is represented. The network would benefit from: adding the missing reaction producing mol_017, breaking rxn_017 into realistic sub-steps, and specifying all catalytic agents. Despite these issues, 5 of 10 pathways achieve sufficient confidence for approval, and the core chemistry is sound.\",\n    \"approved\": true,\n    \"hub_quality\": 0.84,\n    \"convergence_quality\": 0.78\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluat