oved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_014", "rxn_017"], "suggestions": ["Remove or heavily caveat this pathway", "If chain shortening is intended, provide detailed mechanistic justification", "Replace rxn_014 with a more plausible source of isovaleraldehyde"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_018": 0.7, "rxn_019": 0.6, "rxn_020": 0.55, "rxn_021": 0.75}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.63, "pathway_coherence": 0.72, "environmental_progression": 0.7, "target_achievement": 0.72, "overall_confidence": 0.68, "feedback": "This pathway mirrors the modern biochemical valine biosynthesis (pyruvate \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 valine) but attempts it under hydrothermal conditions without enzymes. While CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite (rxn_018) has some support from Muchowska et al. and Varma et al., the pyruvate condensation to acetolactate (rxn_019) and the subsequent rearrangement/reduction to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (rxn_020) are biochemical steps requiring enzymes (acetolactate synthase, ketol-acid reductoisomerase) with no demonstrated prebiotic equivalent. The final reductive amination (rxn_021) is more plausible.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_019", "rxn_020"], "suggestions": ["Provide experimental evidence for non-enzymatic acetolactate formation from pyruvate", "Consider whether metal sulfide catalysis could mediate rearrangement", "This pathway would benefit from explicit mineral catalyst specifications"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_018": 0.7, "rxn_019": 0.6, "rxn_020": 0.55, "rxn_024": 0.8, "rxn_015": 0.9, "rxn_012": 0.9}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.72, "pathway_coherence": 0.8, "environmental_progression": 0.85, "target_achievement": 0.85, "overall_confidence": 0.78, "feedback": "Interesting cross-environment pathway: hydrothermal pyruvate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 surface decarboxylation to isobutyraldehyde \u2192 Strecker to valine. The downstream portion (decarbox